<div class="ch-panel" id="ch0">
  <div class="ch-header">
    <div class="ch-tag">Chapter 00 // Introduction // Initializing...</div>
    <div class="ch-title">CASE FILE OPENS</div>
    <div class="ch-sub">In which Detective Mark takes on the oldest cold case in recorded history</div>
    <div class="ch-header-line"><span></span><span></span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="story">

    <p class="log">It was raining the day they called me in. The kind of rain that perfectly sets the scene for a crime mystery.</p>

    <p>Hello everyone, let me introduce myself. My name is Mark. Better known as Detective Mark. I work in the deep depths of the human body — the stem cell districts, the quiet alleys where cells work to divide day and night to keep the body running. Around 37 trillion human cell residents reside in this metropolis of skin, each with their own jobs to do, following the same rules. Most of them cooperate, divide when they're told to divide, die when they're told to die, keep to their districts. A beautiful, brutal social contract that's been running for the last 600 million years.</p>

    <p class="log">Most of the cells follow the rules. Only, most of them...</p>

    <p>The case I'm about to walk you through is perhaps one of the oldest in the books. It predates nations, whole family lineages, even fossils. Multicellular life has existed for 600 million years and this same crime repeatedly keeps showing up at the scene.</p>

    <div class="suspect">
      <div class="suspect-name">CANCER</div>
      <table>
        <tr><td>STATUS</td><td class="status">WANTED // ACTIVE // ALL JURISDICTIONS</td></tr>
        <tr><td>LAST SEEN</td><td>In virtually every multicellular organism ever recorded</td></tr>
        <tr><td>EVIDENCE TRAIL</td><td>Tumours found in fossilised dinosaur vertebrae (Rothschild et al., 2003). Crime predates human history.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>KNOWN ALIASES</td><td>"Random Error" / "Bad Luck" / "Malfunction" / "Accident"</td></tr>
        <tr><td>DISTINGUISHING FEATURE</td><td>NOT a foreign invader. Originates from inside the host organism. An inside job.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>MOTIVE</td><td>None. Following original programming.</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The strange part of this case is that it isn't a guessing game. We aren't trying to find the culprit — we already know who it is. We've known the suspect for a long time. The culprit just so happens to be one of our own cells.</p>

    <div class="dispatch">
      What every textbook gets wrong: they treat cancer like an accident. A random error. A molecule misfiring. Bad luck in a dark alley. There is truth to that. But it misses the deeper story. The deeper story is that the cell that becomes cancer was built to do almost everything it ends up doing. Divide without stopping. Resist death. Renew itself repeatedly. These aren't criminal acts it learned on the street. They're its original programming. The programming that keeps you alive.
    </div>

    <p>Cancer has affected humans since prehistoric times, but prevalence has increased dramatically in recent decades. Part of the explanation is simple — people live longer. The longer the body runs, the more opportunities cells have to accumulate mutations (Hulvat, 2020). In the past half century, case files have multiplied with changes in human behaviour and the environment — increased exposure to carcinogens, from pollution to chemicals in consumer products (Franken et al., 2017). Still, these factors only explain part of the picture.</p>

    <div class="terminal-log">
      <div class="prompt">>> DET.MARK // PERSONAL LOG // STEM CELL DISTRICTS</div>
      <p>Stem cells are the body's maintenance crew. Intestinal lining: replaced every 5 days. Bone marrow: 200 billion red blood cells per day. They divide fast, live long, and refuse to die on command (McCulloch & Till, 2005). The exact properties evolution spent hundreds of millions of years building — the ones genuinely keeping you alive right now — are the same properties that make cancer not just possible, but inevitable over a long enough timeline.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="course-box">
      <div class="label">>> COURSE CONNECTION // HSCI 324</div>
      <p>This case connects to the HSCI 324 theme that <strong>adaptations shaped by selection can carry disadvantages under certain circumstances.</strong> Properties of stem cells were selected for because of their benefits to survival, but the cost is cancer that becomes probable over a human lifespan of many accumulated divisions.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="log">That is the case. Not what cancer does — but why cancer is the inevitable consequence of the very system that keeps you alive. We've got a case to crack.</p>

