    <p>To continuously undergo this workload, stem cells possess abilities that most other cells do not. They are able to divide repeatedly, resulting in infinite self-renewal, and survive for long periods. Simultaneously, they generate specialised daughter cells that replace damaged or ageing tissue (Poliwoda et al., 2022). From an evolutionary perspective, these abilities represent adaptations strongly favoured by natural selection.</p>

    <p class="log">But these privileges come with a cost.</p>

    <p>Every time a stem cell divides, its DNA must be copied. Although highly accurate, mutation errors may occur. Over millions of divisions across a lifetime, these errors accumulate and introduce genetic variation amongst cells. While most mutations may be harmless, some affect genes controlling cell growth or survival. When this occurs, a mutated cell may gain a selective advantage over neighbouring cells and begin expanding within the tissue environment (Greaves &amp; Maley, 2012).</p>

