<!-- ══════════════════════════
     CH 02 — TRADE-OFF
══════════════════════════ -->
<div class="ch-panel" id="ch2">
  <div class="ch-header">
    <div class="ch-tag">Chapter 02 // Evolutionary Trade-Off // Analysing Evidence...</div>
    <div class="ch-title">THE LONG GAME</div>
    <div class="ch-sub">In which we discover the suspect is also the body's most essential asset</div>
    <div class="ch-header-line"><span></span><span></span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="story">
    <p class="log">By the case folder, I could already tell this suspect was extraordinary.</p>
    <p>Most cells in this city live by the rules — dividing when told, stopping when signalled, dying when damaged. But stem cells operate under a different set of permissions, with the authority to divide, persist, and rebuild. The body relies on these cells to maintain tissues that constantly experience damage or loss.</p>
    <p>The same features that make stem cells indispensable also make them dangerous. Rapid proliferation keeps tissues supplied with fresh cells, but every additional division creates another opportunity for replication error. Self-renewal prevents the stem pool from being depleted — but also means any mutation can be preserved and copied forward indefinitely. Resistance to cell death protects valuable regenerative cells during stress, yet that same survival capacity becomes a liability if the wrong genetic changes accumulate (Reya et al., 2001).</p>

    <div class="case-box" data-label="// Evidence Exhibit C — Double Agent File">
      <h4>Stem Cell Traits: Dual-Use Analysis</h4>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Trait</th><th>Survival Benefit</th><th class="flag">Cancer Risk</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Rapid proliferation</td><td>Gut lining renewed every 4–5 days; continuous tissue supply</td><td class="flag">Every division = replication error opportunity</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Self-renewal</td><td>Prevents depletion; ensures lifelong tissue maintenance</td><td class="flag">Mutations propagate to ALL descendant cells indefinitely</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Apoptosis resistance</td><td>Protects regenerative cells during injury and stress</td><td class="flag">TP53 mutation (&gt;50% of cancers) makes this unconditional</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Telomerase activity</td><td>Prevents telomere shortening during repeated divisions</td><td class="flag">~85–90% of cancers reactivate TERT for immortality</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Epigenetic plasticity</td><td>Open chromatin enables multi-lineage differentiation</td><td class="flag">Exploited by cancer to dedifferentiate to stem-like states</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>When mutations occur in long-lived stem cells, they can persist for decades. A single mutation in a stem cell can be inherited by many future cells within the same tissue. Research comparing different tissues has shown that organs with higher numbers of lifetime stem cell divisions tend to show higher cancer incidence — suggesting that normal tissue maintenance itself contributes to cancer probability (Greaves &amp; Maley, 2012).</p>

    <div class="dispatch">From an evolutionary perspective, this reflects a fundamental biological compromise. Natural selection favours traits that improve survival and reproductive success early in life. However, the same biological traits that provide these benefits may carry long-term costs that appear later in life — when natural selection is weaker.</div>

    <p>This evolutionary compromise is known as <span class="term">antagonistic pleiotropy</span> — a single biological trait provides advantages early in life but produces harmful consequences later. Stem cell biology fits this pattern: self-renewal, rapid proliferation, and long-term persistence allows tissues to function across decades, yet creates the conditions under which cancer can eventually emerge (Aktipis et al., 2015).</p>

    <p><span class="term">TP53</span> — the "guardian of the genome" — detects DNA damage and triggers apoptosis in cells too damaged to repair. It is the most frequently mutated gene in human cancers, with mutation occurring in more than half of all tumours (Vousden &amp; Prives, 2009).</p>

    <div class="terminal-log">
      <div class="prompt">>> CASE SUMMARY // DET.MARK</div>
      <p>The body did not evolve stem cells to cause disease. Cancer emerged as an unintended consequence of biological systems selected because they help organisms survive. Benefits appear immediately: tissues regenerate, wounds heal, organs continue functioning. The costs may only become visible decades later. This is the trade-off that multicellular life accepts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="sources">
      <div class="sources-label">// References</div>
      <p>Aktipis, C. A. et al. (2015). Cancer across the tree of life. <em>Phil. Trans. Royal Society B, 370</em>(1673), 20140219.</p>
      <p>Reya, T. et al. (2001). Stem cells, cancer, and cancer stem cells. <em>Nature, 414</em>(6859), 105–111.</p>
      <p>Vousden, K. H., &amp; Prives, C. (2009). Blinded by the Light: The Growing Complexity of p53. <em>Cell, 137</em>(3), 413–431.</p>
    </div>
