<!-- ══════════════════════════
     CH 03 — SOMATIC EVOLUTION
══════════════════════════ -->
<div class="ch-panel" id="ch3">
  <div class="ch-header">
    <div class="ch-tag">Chapter 03 // Somatic Evolution // Tracking Signal...</div>
    <div class="ch-title">EVOLUTION'S BLACK MARKET</div>
    <div class="ch-sub">In which the body has been running its own underground evolution for decades</div>
    <div class="ch-header-line"><span></span><span></span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="story">
    <p class="log">I have been on this beat long enough to know that crime doesn't appear out of nowhere. It organises itself. It evolves.</p>
    <p>A mutation that starts as a minor bookkeeping error becomes, twenty years later, the operation controlling the entire district. Cancer works in much the same way. It doesn't emerge all at once — it develops gradually. A Darwinian evolutionary process, taking place within the tissue of a single organism, often over many years or even decades. And for evolution to run, three ingredients are required. When I checked the file, the tumour had all three.</p>

    <div class="case-box" data-label="// Darwin's Three Conditions — Verified in Tumour">
      <h4>Conditions for Evolution — All Present</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>VARIATION:</strong> Every stem cell division introduces somatic mutations. No two cells in an aged stem cell compartment are genetically identical. Raw material for selection is continuously generated.</li>
        <li><strong>HERITABILITY:</strong> When a stem cell divides, its mutations are passed to daughter cells. An advantageous mutation propagates through the entire descendant lineage. Traits are heritable at the cellular level.</li>
        <li><strong>DIFFERENTIAL REPRODUCTION:</strong> A cell with faster division, apoptosis resistance, or immune evasion outcompetes its neighbours. Its lineage expands. Darwin's engine turns over inside the body.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>A tumour is not a uniform mass of identical abnormal cells. Rather, it represents a population — a Darwinian ecosystem characterised by genetic diversity and ongoing selection pressure. Different regions carry distinct mutation profiles, while subclonal populations compete within the tumour microenvironment. Cells with advantageous traits dominate. Even a small growth advantage compounds dramatically over cellular generations. This is why cancer is primarily associated with ageing — somatic evolution takes time, and long-lived humans provide that time (Alberts et al., 2002).</p>

    <h3>// The Treatment Problem</h3>

    <p>Here is what makes this case particularly hard to close. <strong style="color:var(--red)">Treatment becomes part of the crime scene.</strong></p>
    <p>Chemotherapy acts as a strong selective pressure on this evolving population. A drug that kills 95% of a tumour does not end the evolutionary process — it changes it. Drug-sensitive cells die, but the 5% carrying pre-existing resistance mutations suddenly have access to more space and nutrients. These surviving cells expand. Over time, resistant clones become the dominant population — demonstrating evolution in action. This is why treatment can unintentionally drive selection of drug-resistant cancer cells and lead to tumour recurrence (O'Brien et al., 2006).</p>

    <div class="dispatch">The cancer didn't develop resistance. It was SELECTED for it. The resistant subclone was always there — a minor variant in the tumour population, waiting for the right conditions to expand. That is Darwin's racket: turn your treatment strategy against you.</div>

    <div class="terminal-log">
      <div class="prompt">>> ADAPTIVE THERAPY // CLASSIFIED APPROACH</div>
      <p>Most promising new approach: <strong>adaptive therapy</strong> (Gatenby et al., 2009). Does not aim to eradicate the tumour completely. Instead: manage it. Keep treatment-sensitive cells alive to compete with resistant clones. Exploit the tumour's own evolutionary dynamics as a weapon against it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="sources">
      <div class="sources-label">// References</div>
      <p>Alberts B. et al. (2002). <em>Molecular Biology of the Cell</em> (4th ed.). Garland Science.</p>
      <p>Gatenby, R. A. et al. (2009). Adaptive therapy. <em>Cancer Research, 69</em>(11), 4894–4903.</p>
      <p>O'Brien, M. E. et al. (2006). Mortality within 30 days of chemotherapy. <em>British Journal of Cancer, 95</em>(12), 1632–1636.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
