<!-- ══════════════════════════
     CH 04 — DISPUTES
══════════════════════════ -->
<div class="ch-panel" id="ch4">
  <div class="ch-header">
    <div class="ch-tag">Chapter 04 // Scientific Disputes // Cross-referencing Testimonies...</div>
    <div class="ch-title">CONFLICTING WITNESSES</div>
    <div class="ch-sub">No case is totally clean. Evidence can point two ways at once.</div>
    <div class="ch-header-line"><span></span><span></span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="story">
    <p class="log">No case is totally clean. Witnesses contradict each other; evidence can point two ways at once. A good detective views both contradictions and doesn't ignore them. Here are the open disputes on the file.</p>

    <div class="dispute-h">// DISPUTE 01 — BAD LUCK vs. LIFESTYLE</div>
    <div class="dispute-sub">How much of cancer risk comes from intrinsic cell division vs. the environment?</div>
    <div class="witness-grid">
      <div class="witness for">
        <div class="w-label">[WITNESS A] The Intrinsic Division View</div>
        <p>Tomasetti and Vogelstein (2015) found that tissues undergoing more lifetime stem cell divisions tend to have higher cancer rates regardless of known environmental exposures. The majority of driver mutations arise not from environmental mutagens but from unavoidable replication errors. Many cancers arise from the unavoidable mathematics of DNA replication — the price of maintaining living tissues (Tomasetti et al., 2017).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="witness against">
        <div class="w-label">[WITNESS B] Environment Matters</div>
        <p>The "bad luck" framing was criticised for not appropriately weighing environmental and lifestyle contributions — especially for cancers with well-established environmental causes like lung cancer, hepatocellular carcinoma, and skin cancer (Couzin-Frankel, 2015). Tobacco, UV radiation, chronic infection, and diet can amplify the baseline mutation rate well beyond what stem cell divisions alone produce (Song &amp; Giovannucci, 2016; Wu et al., 2016). Calling it bad luck undermines real preventive value.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assessment"><div class="a-label">>> DET.MARK ASSESSMENT</div>Both witnesses are telling the truth about different parts of the same case. Intrinsic replication errors set a baseline cancer risk that exists even without environmental exposure. Environmental factors act to elevate that baseline. The framework explains the floor; environment explains why some people hit it much sooner.</div>

    <div class="dispute-h">// DISPUTE 02 — DOES A BOSS CELL RUN THE TUMOUR?</div>
    <div class="witness-grid">
      <div class="witness for">
        <div class="w-label">[WITNESS A] The Hierarchy Model</div>
        <p>According to the cancer stem cell (CSC) model, tumours are organised like a hierarchy. A small subpopulation of cancer stem cells — CD44+/CD24− in breast cancer, CD133+ in glioblastoma — maintain the tumour, drive regrowth after treatment, and are responsible for metastasis (Al-Hajj et al., 2003; Singh et al., 2003). Strong evidence supports this in leukaemia, glioblastoma, and breast cancer (Lapidot et al., 1994).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="witness against">
        <div class="w-label">[WITNESS B] The Plasticity Model</div>
        <p>Others argue the hierarchy is not fixed. Under stress — especially after chemotherapy — ordinary tumour cells can dedifferentiate and revert to a stem-cell-like state. CSC identity is a dynamic state, not a defined subpopulation. Targeting surface markers alone won't eliminate the operation because remaining cells can re-acquire stem-like properties. The hierarchy exists, but it is fluid (Gupta et al., 2011).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assessment"><div class="a-label">>> DET.MARK ASSESSMENT</div>Evidence suggests both models operate simultaneously. The hierarchy and plasticity models aren't mutually exclusive. What matters more depends on tumour type and clinical context. The case is still open.</div>

    <div class="dispute-h">// DISPUTE 03 — IS ANTAGONISTIC PLEIOTROPY THE RIGHT FRAMEWORK?</div>
    <div class="witness-grid">
      <div class="witness for">
        <div class="w-label">[WITNESS A] The Trade-Off Framework</div>
        <p>Supporters argue that stem cell properties are actively maintained by selection throughout reproductive life — not neutral post-reproductive drift (Williams, 1957). Cancer affects reproductive-age individuals too, so the cost is not exclusively post-reproductive. Rapid division and self-renewal keep organisms alive long enough to reproduce; cancer risk is tied to these same properties — a genuine evolutionary trade-off (Ungewitter &amp; Scrable, 2008).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="witness against">
        <div class="w-label">[WITNESS B] Neutral Drift Argument</div>
        <p>Others argue the story may be simpler. If most cancer mortality occurs after reproductive age, natural selection pressure against cancer-enabling properties is very weak (Medawar, 1952). The relationship may not be a true evolutionary trade-off but rather neutral late-life consequences of traits that selection simply can't see well enough to modify (Austad &amp; Hoffman, 2018).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assessment"><div class="a-label">>> DET.MARK ASSESSMENT</div>A legitimate theoretical dispute. Some aspects of cancer risk reflect genuine trade-offs; others may be closer to neutral late-life consequences. The distinction matters for how we theorise about the evolutionary origins of cancer. The case is far from closed.</div>

    <div class="sources">
      <div class="sources-label">// References</div>
      <p>Al-Hajj, M. et al. (2003). <em>PNAS, 100</em>(7). · Austad, S. N., &amp; Hoffman, J. M. (2018). <em>Evol. Med. Public Health</em>. · Couzin-Frankel, J. (2015). <em>Science, 347</em>.</p>
      <p>Gupta, P. B. et al. (2011). <em>Cell, 146</em>(4). · Lapidot, T. et al. (1994). <em>Nature, 367</em>. · Medawar, P. B. (1952). <em>An unsolved problem of biology.</em></p>
      <p>Singh, S. K. et al. (2003). <em>Cancer Research, 63</em>. · Tomasetti &amp; Vogelstein (2015). <em>Science, 347</em>. · Tomasetti et al. (2017). <em>Science, 355</em>.</p>
      <p>Ungewitter &amp; Scrable (2008). <em>Mech. Ageing Dev., 129</em>. · Williams, G. C. (1957). <em>Evolution, 11</em>. · Wu, S. et al. (2016). <em>Nature, 529</em>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
