<div class="ch-panel" id="ch5">
  <div class="ch-header">
    <div class="ch-tag">Chapter 05 // Assessment // Interrogation Protocol Active</div>
    <div class="ch-title">THE INTERROGATION ROOM</div>
    <div class="ch-sub">Five questions. Click to unlock each answer.</div>
    <div class="ch-header-line"><span></span><span></span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="story">
    <p class="log" style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Click any question to access the classified answer. Badge indicates question type.</p>

    <div class="qa-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="qa-q">
        <span class="qa-q-text">Q1. From an evolutionary perspective, why has natural selection not eliminated the cancer risk associated with stem cell division?</span>
        <div class="qa-meta"><span class="qa-badge b-recall">Recall</span><span class="qa-arrow">▶</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-a">
        <div class="qa-a-label">>> ANSWER UNLOCKED</div>
        <p>Stem cell division is essential for survival, and cancer predominantly occurs after reproductive age. Evolution favours a balance between tissue regeneration and mutation risk rather than full protection from cancer. The properties that enable stem cells to maintain tissues — rapid division, self-renewal, apoptosis resistance — are the same properties that increase cancer probability over time. Natural selection cannot remove the cancer risk without also removing the survival benefit. This is antagonistic pleiotropy applied to stem cell biology.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="qa-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="qa-q">
        <span class="qa-q-text">Q2. Imagine a mutation occurs in a stem cell in the intestinal lining that increases its rate of division. Predict what might happen to the population of cells in that tissue over time, and explain why.</span>
        <div class="qa-meta"><span class="qa-badge b-apply">Apply</span><span class="qa-arrow">▶</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-a">
        <div class="qa-a-label">>> ANSWER UNLOCKED</div>
        <p>The mutated stem cell undergoes <strong>clonal expansion</strong> — dividing faster than neighbours, it gradually produces more daughter cells and gains a <strong>competitive advantage</strong> within the intestinal crypt. As the clone expands, each subsequent division carries the original mutation plus new opportunities for additional errors, leading to <strong>increased mutation accumulation</strong>. If further mutations affect growth regulation or apoptosis, the clone may eventually escape normal tissue constraints, increasing the probability of <strong>tumour formation</strong>. This is somatic evolution in action: variation, heritability, and differential reproduction at the cellular level.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="qa-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="qa-q">
        <span class="qa-q-text">Q3. If cancer exists, does it mean evolution failed to optimise the human body? True or False — explain your answer.</span>
        <div class="qa-meta"><span class="qa-badge b-tf">T / F</span><span class="qa-arrow">▶</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-a">
        <div class="qa-a-label">>> ANSWER UNLOCKED // FALSE</div>
        <p><strong>False.</strong> Evolution does not optimise for longevity or freedom from disease — it optimises for reproductive success. The stem cell system that makes cancer possible is the same system that allows organisms to survive injuries, regenerate tissues, and live long enough to reproduce. Cancer most often emerges late in life, after reproductive age, when natural selection exerts much weaker pressure. The existence of cancer does not indicate a failure of evolution — it reflects an inherent trade-off within a system that was well-optimised for the conditions under which it evolved.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="qa-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="qa-q">
        <span class="qa-q-text">Q4. Most mutations that occur in cells are harmful. True or False — explain your answer.</span>
        <div class="qa-meta"><span class="qa-badge b-tf">T / F</span><span class="qa-arrow">▶</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-a">
        <div class="qa-a-label">>> ANSWER UNLOCKED // FALSE</div>
        <p><strong>False.</strong> The vast majority of somatic mutations that accumulate across a lifetime are <strong>neutral</strong> — they occur in non-coding regions of the genome, or in coding regions where they do not alter protein function in a meaningful way. Only a small fraction — called <strong>driver mutations</strong> — affect genes that regulate cell growth or survival in ways that confer a selective advantage. Passenger mutations are far more common. This is why not every stem cell division leads to cancer, and why it typically takes decades and multiple driver mutations for a tumour to initiate.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="qa-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="qa-q">
        <span class="qa-q-text">Q5. If adaptive therapy aims to control tumour evolution rather than eliminate the tumour, when might a physician still choose standard chemotherapy, and what factors would influence that decision?</span>
        <div class="qa-meta"><span class="qa-badge b-think">Critical</span><span class="qa-arrow">▶</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-a">
        <div class="qa-a-label">>> ANSWER UNLOCKED</div>
        <p><strong>Tumour growth rate:</strong> If the tumour is growing rapidly and poses an immediate threat to organ function or life, aggressive elimination may take priority over evolutionary management.</p>
        <p><strong>Risk of resistance:</strong> If the tumour shows low genetic heterogeneity and no pre-existing resistant subclones are detected, standard therapy may achieve durable remission before resistance can evolve.</p>
        <p><strong>Patient condition:</strong> Adaptive therapy requires ongoing monitoring and multiple treatment cycles. If the patient cannot sustain long-term follow-up, a more decisive upfront approach may be necessary.</p>
        <p><strong>Curability:</strong> For certain cancers (e.g., some leukaemias, testicular cancer, early-stage lymphomas), standard chemotherapy offers high cure rates. Adaptive therapy is most relevant for advanced, incurable cancers where long-term control — not cure — is the realistic aim.</p>
