  <div class="story">
    <p class="log">600 million years. Hundreds of millions of organisms. The same crime, committed again and again, in every lineage of multicellular life that has ever existed.</p>

    <p>And after all this time working the case, here is what the evidence tells me. Cancer is not a malfunction. It is not bad luck in a back alley. It is the predictable long-term consequence of the most important biological system the body has — the stem cell maintenance network that keeps every organ functioning across a human lifetime.</p>

    <div class="case-box" data-label="// Final Report — SCU-10-∞">
      <h4>Summary of Evidence</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Stem cells must divide continuously to maintain tissues. Each division risks a copying error. Over decades, these errors accumulate.</li>
        <li>The properties that make stem cells essential — self-renewal, rapid proliferation, apoptosis resistance, telomerase activity — are the same properties that increase cancer probability over a long enough timeline.</li>
        <li>This is antagonistic pleiotropy: evolution selected for traits that benefit survival and reproduction early in life, accepting the long-term cost of cancer that appears largely after reproductive age.</li>
        <li>Cancer progression follows Darwinian logic — somatic evolution, clonal selection, and treatment resistance are expressions of natural selection operating at the cellular level.</li>
        <li>The scientific community continues to debate: intrinsic errors vs. environment, hierarchy vs. plasticity, true trade-off vs. neutral drift. The case is open on multiple fronts.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>The body did not evolve to cause cancer. But the system it evolved to survive with carries cancer as an inescapable shadow. Evolution has had 600 million years to solve this problem.</p>

    <div class="alert-box"><p>IT HAS NOT SOLVED IT — BECAUSE FROM EVOLUTION'S PERSPECTIVE, THERE IS NOTHING TO SOLVE.</p></div>

    <p>The deal is working exactly as intended. Organisms repair, regenerate, reproduce. The cancer bill arrives later. Natural selection, working on timescales of generations rather than lifetimes, has never had strong enough reason to intervene. For us — the organisms living the full lifespan — the investigation continues.</p>

    <div class="course-box">
      <div class="label">>> FINAL COURSE CONNECTION // HSCI 324</div>
      <p>This case is a concrete example of the course theme: <strong>adaptations shaped by natural selection can carry disadvantages under certain circumstances.</strong> Stem cell properties were selected for their survival benefits across reproductive life. The disadvantage — cancer — becomes probable only over a long lifespan of accumulated divisions, appearing largely after the period of greatest selective pressure.</p>
    </div>

